Being Picky About Free Textbooks From Springer

Author

Desmond Choy

Published

April 30, 2020

You might have heard that Springer Nature, an American German academic publishing company, is giving free access to more than 500 key textbooks across Springer Natureâs eBook subject collections, as their way to support lecturers, teachers and students and grant remote access to essential educational resources during this Covid-19 lockdown period. A repository of the books can be found here.

To my delight, I stumbled across the springerQuarantineBooksR package made by Renan Xavier Cortes in a blog post. After a preliminary scan of the package, I thought this would make for a good opportunity to practise some exploratory data analysis to explore ways to narrow down a search across hundreds of books and their descriptions.

1 Import libaries & data

#devtools::install_github("renanxcortes/springerQuarantineBooksR")
library(springerQuarantineBooksR)
library(tidyverse)
theme_set(theme_minimal())

2 Examining dataset

Once the package is installed, you are now able to download the entire batch of books all at once with this line of code.

#setwd('path_of_your_choice')
#download_springer_book_files()

Diving a bit deeper into the package has to offer, I noticed the dataset consists of only 407 rows and 391 unique book titles available for download - not quite the >500 aforementioned textbooks that was cited in the article linked above.

I looked around at the Github repo and found this explanation by the author:

âCurrently, due to the fact that the package works with the book title (in order to facilitate the creation of subgroups of books by title), It fetches the latest edition of each book. In fact, thatâs why the number of books generated is lower than the number of lines of the .xlsx file catalog that springer made available. Perhaps, it is worth to check an alternative to download all editions of the same book.â

So if one is looking for a book, itâs better to search for sub-categories under subject_classification. However, multiple sub-categories are listed under subject_classification column per book. I plan to separate() then pivot_longer() to make our data tidy.

springer2 <- springer %>%
  separate(subject_classification, paste("category", 1:8, sep = ""), sep = ";")

springer2 %>% 
  select(book_title, english_package_name, contains("cat"))

Another way to scan for missing values would be using the map_df() function by the purrr package. Once again we obtain the same outcome.

springer2 %>% 
  select(contains("cat")) %>% 
  map_df(~sum(is.na(.)))

2.1 Data visualization

Iâll proceed to remove that column, followed by making our data long with pivot_longer() so that we can process it later.

springer_tidy <- springer2 %>%
  select(-category8) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    9:15,
    names_to = "cat",
    values_to = "categories",
    values_drop_na = T
  )

springer_tidy %>% 
  select(book_title, english_package_name, categories) %>% 
  add_count(categories) %>%
  filter(n > 10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(categories, n), n/n, fill = fct_lump_n(english_package_name, 10))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Exploring the springerQuarantineBooksR package",
    subtitle = "The free e-books feature a good mix across all disciplines",
    fill = "Broad Categories",
    x = "Sub-categories",
    y = "Number of Times Mentioned"
  )

Some observations:

  • Physics, Mathematics, Chemistry and Statistics are very straightforward categories - you wonât be surprised
  • Categories like Mathematical & Computer Engineering and Statistics & Computing, on the other hand, are inter-disciplinary.

To narrow down potentially interesting sub-categories, I created word clouds to highlight the most popular ones, in the event anyone is looking for inspiration on topics to dive into.

3.1 Top 6 most popular categories

library(ggwordcloud)

wordcloud <- springer_tidy %>% 
  mutate(popular = fct_lump_n(english_package_name, 5)) %>% 
  group_by(popular, categories) %>% 
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>% 
  group_by(popular) %>% 
  slice_max(n = 20, order_by = count) %>% 
  ungroup()

3.2 Most popular sub-categories within top 6 categories

ggplot(wordcloud, aes(
  label = categories,
  size = count,
  colour = popular
)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud_area(rm_outside = TRUE,
                           eccentricity = 1,
                           shape = "pentagon",
  ) +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 20) +
  facet_wrap(. ~ popular, nrow = 3) +
  labs(title = "Analysis paralysis setting in with hundred of books to choose from?", subtitle = "Word clouds are a way to visualize text data; Size of the word is an indication of its popularity in each category") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 25, hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 15, hjust = 0.5),
    strip.background = element_blank(),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 20)
  )

3.3 Potentially esoteric sub-categories within top 6 categories

And just because my wife was curious what the most âobsureâ sub-categories were â¦

esoteric <- springer_tidy %>%
  mutate(popular = fct_lump_n(english_package_name, 5)) %>%
  group_by(popular, categories) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  filter(count < 4) %>%
  group_by(popular) %>%
  slice_max(n = 10, order_by = count) %>%
  ungroup()

ggplot(esoteric,
       aes(
         label = categories,
         size = count,
         colour = popular
       )) +
  geom_text_wordcloud_area(
    rm_outside = T,
    eccentricity = 1,
    shape = "pentagon"
  ) +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 20) +
  facet_wrap(. ~ popular, nrow = 3) +
  labs(title = "What are some potentially esoteric sub-categories?", subtitle = "These are a sample of sub-categories that are cited three times or less.") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 25, hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 15, hjust = 0.5),
    strip.background = element_blank(),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 20)
  )

Once youâve decided on a category, say Sociology, the following code brings up the book title, author, and the relevant download link

library(kableExtra)

springer_tidy %>%
  filter(str_detect(categories, "Sociology")) %>%
  distinct(book_title, english_package_name, open_url) %>% 
  mutate(open_url = cell_spec("SpringerLink", "html", link = open_url)) %>%
  kbl(escape = FALSE) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"))
